Akihiro encouraged {{ill|Confucianism|ja|儒学|12=draft|12=draft}} within his domain. In {{ill|Tenmei|ja|天明|12=draft|12=draft}} 8 (1788), he invited {{ill|Akutagawa Motodō|ja|芥川元澄|12=draft|12=draft}} from Kyoto as a Confucian scholar to lecture his retainers. This marked the foundation of the domain's academy, {{ill|Shintokukan (Sabae Domain)|ja|進徳館|12=draft|12=draft}}. Akihiro himself was said to excel in mounted archery.
Akihiro passed away in {{ill|Bunka|ja|文化|1=Bunka|2=ja|3=文化 (元号)|4=de|5=Bunka (Ära)|6=ko|7=분카|12=draft|12=draft}} 8 (1812) on the 21st day of the 12th month at the age of 42. He was succeeded by his eldest son, {{ill|Manabe Akinobu|ja|間部詮允|12=draft|12=draft}}. His posthumous Buddhist name was Shinrei-in (真霊院), and he is buried at {{ill|Mankeiji Temple|ja|万慶寺|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Sabae|ja|鯖江市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Fukui Prefecture.
== Family == '''Parents:''' * Father: {{ill|Manabe Akishige|ja|間部詮茂|12=draft|12=draft}} * Mother: Mizutani family (concubine)
'''Wife:''' * Tankan-in (daughter of {{ill|Makino Sadanaga|ja|牧野貞長|12=draft|12=draft}})
'''Concubines:''' * Kondō family * Nagata family
'''Children:''' * {{ill|Manabe Akinobu|ja|間部詮允|12=draft|12=draft}} (eldest son, by Kondō) * {{ill|Manabe Akitomo|ja|間部詮苞|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Manabe Akikatsu|ja|間部詮勝|12=draft|12=draft}} (fifth son, by Nagata) * Mine (wife of {{ill|Mizuno Tadamichi|ja|水野忠篤|12=draft|12=draft}}) * Kei (adopted daughter of {{ill|Nakanishi Shun|ja|中西主水|12=draft|12=draft}}) * Chie * Ya * Fumi
